04995nam a22006615i 9780226547404DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017040680  a9780226547404  a(DE-B1597)523235  a(OCoLC)1035556708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJA74.5b.B458 2018 4aJA74.5b.B458 2019 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a320.01223  aCC 79202rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17695:1 ade Beistegui, Miguel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Government of Desire :bA Genealogy of the Liberal Subject /cMiguel de Beistegui. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Why Desire? -- tPart One Homo Oeconomicus -- t1 The Birth of Homo Oeconomicus -- t2 Man’s “Vain and Insatiable Desires,” or the “Oeconomy of Greatness” -- t3 Neoliberal Governmentality -- tPart Two Homo Sexualis -- t4 “Abnormal Desires” and “Barbarous Instincts” -- t5 Instincts or Drives? -- tPart Three Homo Symbolicus -- t6 Recognition, That “Most Ardent Desire” -- t7 Struggles for Recognition -- t8 The Consolations of Recognition -- tConclusion: Desire, Again ... -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiberalism, Miguel de Beistegui argues in The Government of Desire, is best described as a technique of government directed towards the self, with desire as its central mechanism. Whether as economic interest, sexual drive, or the basic longing for recognition, desire is accepted as a core component of our modern self-identities, and something we ought to cultivate. But this has not been true in all times and all places. For centuries, as far back as late antiquity and early Christianity, philosophers believed that desire was an impulse that needed to be suppressed in order for the good life, whether personal or collective, ethical or political, to flourish. Though we now take it for granted, desire as a constitutive dimension of human nature and a positive force required a radical transformation, which coincided with the emergence of liberalism. By critically exploring Foucault’s claim that Western civilization is a civilization of desire, de Beistegui crafts a provocative and original genealogy of this shift in thinking. He shows how the relationship between identity, desire, and government has been harnessed and transformed in the modern world, shaping our relations with others and ourselves, and establishing desire as an essential driving force for the constitution of a new and better social order. But is it? The Government of Desire argues that this is precisely what a contemporary politics of resistance must seek to overcome. By questioning the supposed universality of a politics based on recognition and the economic satisfaction of desire, de Beistegui raises the crucial question of how we can manage to be less governed today, and explores contemporary forms of counter-conduct. ​Drawing on a host of thinkers from philosophy, political theory, and psychoanalysis, and concluding with a call for a sovereign and anarchic form of desire, The Government of Desire is a groundbreaking account of our freedom and unfreedom, of what makes us both governed and ungovernable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aRecognition (Philosophy) 0aRecognition (Philosophy). 0aSexxPolitical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  a(neo)liberalism.  aFoucault.  adesire.  agenealogy.  agovernmentality.  apower.  arecognition.  aresistance.  asexuality.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook pack